This dataset contains information about point source pollution, providing locations and descriptions about the source. In particular, it contains info about addresses and the types of licenses each source has to pollute (e.g. 'Stormwater Discharge', 'Mineral Mine').

Description taken from source: https://data.imap.maryland.gov/datasets/maryland::maryland-point-source-discharges-point-source-discharges/about

"This dataset provides a digital geospatial representation of regulated facility outfalls using data derived from various source data. The process by which this data set has been developed has been guided by Maryland Department of the Environment (MDE) and is the result of multiple geoprocesses. It is important to note that point locations are approximate and many do not represent exact geographic locations of outfalls, rather the parcel that they are located in. It is also important to note that in some cases, due to the way the data was processed, outfalls and facilities may have the same coordinates, leading to points being stacked."

Part 3: Combining Parts 1 and 2¶

map_osm = folium.Map(location=[39.29, -76.61], zoom_start=12)

for index, point in data.iterrows():
    if point["PermitCate"] == "Mineral Mine":
        folium.Marker(location=[point["LAT"], point["LONG_"]],
            icon=folium.Icon(color='gray'),
            icon_size=(1,1),
            popup="<i>" + point['FAC_NAME'] + " - " + point['PermitCate'] + "</i>").add_to(map_osm)
    elif point["PermitCate"] == "Swimming Pool":
        folium.Marker(location=[point["LAT"], point["LONG_"]],

With this map, I am showing the location and type of point source pollution at this point. Clicking on each point reveals the exact license and facility name. In general, sources related to water treatment are colored blue, mines are grayscale, dumps are green, and power sources are red-orange.
